When close to reaching the maximum user limit in Confluence, the administrator should be notified about it in advance, e.g. via a notification email. Currently there is no warning regarding "Maximum user limit has been reached" until a new user is added to Confluence and the license does not permit an additional user. Pre informing will help the administrator to allocate resources well in advance.

Email links on wiki pages are broken in PDF export. See below for an example

{noformat}
[David Chui|mailto:dchui@localhost.localdomain]
{noformat}

When the page is exported, you get links which look like the one below.

{noformat}
https://dchuimailto%3adchui%40localhost.localdomain/
{noformat}

Of course, you need to activate the link to see that it actually points to an invalid location.

{section}
  {column:width=25%}
    {livesearch:spaceKey=SunCluster}
    h5. Contents
    {children:excerpt=true|all=true}
    h5. [Index]
  {column}
  {column:width=75%}
Use this template in all your pages:
{noformat}
{section}
  {column:width=25%}
    {livesearch:spaceKey=SunCluster}
    h5. Contents
    {children:excerpt=true|all=true}
    h5. [Index]
  {column}
  {column:width=75%}
YOUR CONTENT GOES HERE
  {column}
{section}
{noformat}
  {column}
{section}

I managed to figure out a workaround that involves adding a new page (which I named "Template") that contains the content between and including the {noformat} tags, as follows:

{noformat}
{section}
  {column:width=25%}
    {livesearch:spaceKey=SunCluster}
    h5. Contents
    {children:excerpt=true|all=true}
    h5. [Index]
  {column}
  {column:width=75%}
YOUR CONTENT GOES HERE
  {column}
{section}
{noformat}

and then using an {include} on the page on which I wanted to show the {noformat} content:

{include:Template}

